\description{
Constructs an ASP container from a per-cell \code{srt} object (or a \code{cell_name} that can
be loaded via \code{load5HT()}), identifying protocols in the Master UI sheet whose
\code{stimulus_description} indicates \code{spikeTTL} or \code{TTLstack} and whose \code{keep} flag is
truthy. For each kept protocol row, the function:
\enumerate{
\item extracts the listed sweeps from the cell NWB file,
\item computes per-sweep spike-rate traces via \code{nphys::APanalysis()},
\item builds an aligned local-time trace (\code{raw_trace}) where TTL-containing sweeps
are shifted so TTL onset lands near 0 seconds,
\item recomputes baseline mean and percent-of-baseline metrics within \code{bl_window},
\item stores per-protocol outputs in \code{asp$by_protocol} under a deterministic
\code{protocol_key}.
}
}
\details{
The returned object is designed for downstream plotting (e.g., concatenated protocol
views, per-protocol trace + heat strip) and includes \code{segment_bounds} with sweep-level
start/end times and (when possible) a computed \code{ttl_onset_time}.

\strong{Protocol identification:} protocols are selected from the Master UI sheet by
matching \code{stimulus_description} containing \code{spikeTTL} or \code{TTLstack}, then filtering
rows by a permissive truthy parser of the \code{keep} column (accepts logicals, "yes"/"x",
"keep", non-zero numbers, etc.).

\strong{Sweep parsing:} \code{wrapped_sweeps} is parsed into numeric sweep ids and incremented
by 1 (to match NWB sweep indexing used here).

\strong{Chunk mapping:} \code{stimulus_description} is split on \code{"+"} to produce sweep-level
chunk names; \code{TTLstack} chunks are expanded to unique labels (\code{TTLstack_1}, \code{TTLstack_2}, ...).
TTL-containing sweeps are those labeled \code{spikeTTL} or \verb{TTLstack_*}.

\strong{Time alignment:} the first TTL-containing sweep defines the zero reference for
concatenation; TTL sweeps are additionally shifted by \code{ttlTime} so TTL onset occurs
near 0 seconds within those sweeps. \code{segment_bounds$ttl_onset_time} is computed by
snapping to the sample closest to \code{ttlTime} within each TTL sweep.

\strong{Recomputation:} after assembling the raw trace, \code{instRate} is outlier-filtered,
\code{blMean} is computed over \code{bl_window}, and \code{percent_change} is computed as
\code{(instRate / blMean) * 100} when possible (otherwise \code{NA}).
}
